sponseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholera toxin","Enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli","Excess gastric acid","Rotavirus infection","Shigella infection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShigella\u003C/strong\u003E species cause bacillary dysentery by invading and destroying intestinal epithelial cells, leading to inflammatory diarrhoea with blood and mucus.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotavirus\u003C/strong\u003E causes diarrhoea by infecting mature enterocytes and disrupting sodium-glucose cotransport, rather than through direct mucosal destruction. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholera toxin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eenterotoxigenic \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E cause secretory diarrhoea by increasing chloride secretion and inhibiting sodium absorption, without directly damaging the mucosa. \u003Cstrong\u003EExcess gastric acid\u003C/strong\u003E production, as seen in Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, causes diarrhoea through inactivation of pancreatic enzymes and bile acid precipitation, not through direct mucosal damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Invasive bacterial pathogens like Shigella cause inflammatory diarrhoea by directly damaging intestinal mucosa","Viral gastroenteritis typically causes diarrhoea through disruption of enterocyte function rather than direct mucosal damage","Excess acid production in Zollinger-Ellison syndrome causes diarrhoea through indirect mechanisms"],"references":["DuPont HL. Persistent Diarrhea: A Clinical Review. JAMA. 2016 Jun 28;315(24):2712-23. doi: 10.1001/jama.2016.7833. PMID: 27357241","Nemeth V, Pfleghaar N. Diarrhea. [Updated 2022 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448082/","Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res C